        <section id="about">
            <div class="about-grid">
                <img src="Breitfeld_photo.jpg" alt="Profile Photo" class="profile-img">
                <div>
                    <p>I am a Doctoral Candidate in the Department of Psychology at the University of Wisconsin-Madison. My research focuses on language development, specifically how babies and toddlers begin to learn words in their native language.</p>
                    <p>I received my M.S. in Developmental Psychology from the University of Wisconsin-Madison, advised by Dr. Jenny Saffran. Prior to my current position, I recieved my B.A. in Psychology at Princeton University and completed my undergraduate research in Dr. Casey Lew-Williams's lab.</p>
                    <p>In my research, I am really interested in how children learn language from the complex world around them. I have explored how elements of children's input—the language they hear, the people they hear it from, and the places they hear it in—influence word learning. For example, how does the input children recieve impact which words children learn and what they learn about those words. The goal of this work is to better understand how to best support children's successful word learning and language development. </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="links">
